<h5 class="wp-block-heading" id="aioseo-step">Step 3: Customize the Appearance of Your Fundraising Thermometer</h5>



<p>After setting your fundraising goal and raised amount, it‚Äôs time to adjust a few key settings that make your thermometer easy to read and visually appealing.</p>



<p>Start with the thermometer orientation.</p>



<p>You can choose portrait (vertical) or landscape (horizontal). Portrait is typically the better choice since it resembles the classic thermometer design that donors instantly recognize and expect.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="680" height="294" src="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/configure-fundraising-thermometer-orientation.png" alt="Configure your fundraising thermometer orientation" class="wp-image-370223" srcset="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/configure-fundraising-thermometer-orientation.png 680w, https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/configure-fundraising-thermometer-orientation-300x130.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /></figure>



<p>Next, make sure to show the percentage, target, and amount raised by selecting &#8216;True&#8217; from the dropdown menu.</p>



<p>The percentage gives donors a quick visual look at how close you are to your goal, while the target and raised amounts provide transparency and help build trust.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="680" height="271" src="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/show-your-percentage-in-the-fundraising-thermometer.png" alt="Show your percentage in the fundraising thermometer" class="wp-image-370224" srcset="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/show-your-percentage-in-the-fundraising-thermometer.png 680w, https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/show-your-percentage-in-the-fundraising-thermometer-300x120.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /></figure>



<p>After that, pick a fill color for the thermometer so it stands out on your page.</p>



<p>You can also add a second fill color if you want a subtle gradient effect.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="680" height="369" src="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/customize-colors-for-your-fundraising-thermometer.png" alt="Customize colors for your fundraising thermometer" class="wp-image-370225" srcset="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/customize-colors-for-your-fundraising-thermometer.png 680w, https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/customize-colors-for-your-fundraising-thermometer-300x163.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /></figure>



<p>Finally, adjust the number formatting to keep your amounts clean and easy to read.</p>



<p>This includes setting your currency symbol (like <code>$</code>), choosing a thousands separator (<code>,</code> is easiest to read), and setting decimal places (usually <code>0</code> for whole numbers).</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="680" height="311" src="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/configure-currency-value-for-fundraising-thermometer.png" alt="Configure currency value for your fundraising thermometer" class="wp-image-370226" srcset="https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/configure-currency-value-for-fundraising-thermometer.png 680w, https://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/configure-currency-value-for-fundraising-thermometer-300x137.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /></figure>



<p>These simple adjustments are enough to create a professional-looking thermometer that clearly communicates your fundraising progress. But I recommend taking a look at the other settings and customizing them to your liking.</p>



<p>Once you‚Äôre happy with everything, click the &#8216;Save Changes&#8217; button to store your settings.</p>



<h5 class="wp-block-heading" id="aioseo-step-4">Step 4: Add the Thermometer to Your Site</h5>



